<tr><td valign=top align=left>Korea Telecom was awarded a ten-year BCC in June 1996 to upgrade the network in the northern provinces of Quang Ninh, Hai Phong and Hai Hung by installing 40,000 lines and to provide technology and personnel training to VNPT.  The BCC requires Korea Telecom to provide three years of installation with seven years of maintenance and revenue sharing with VNPT. Estimated project value is $40 million.

<td valign=top align=left>These four operators are in the final stages of negotiating a BCC with VNPT to operate fixed lines in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City. Telstra is slated to install 400,000 lines in West Ho Chi Minh City, while France Telecom is to install 400,000 lines in East Ho Chi Minh City, NTT is negotiating to install 250,000 lines in Hanoi, while Cable & Wireless is also to install lines in Hanoi. Total investment of the projects is expected to be about $1 billion; lines are supposed to be installed by 2000.

<td valign=top align=left>Comvik International Vietnam AB, signed the initial $340 million BCC for nationwide OSM network operation with Vietnam Mobile Services in June 1994. Comvik is committed to investing $159.7 million, $126.4 million of which will go towards equipment purchases. Network capacity is planned to reach 100,000 over the next several years.

<td valign=top align=left>Telstra holds the oldest and most comprehensive telecom cooperation agreement in Vietnam, signed in October 1988. The $197 million BCC with Vietnam Telecommunications International, improves Vietnam's international telecommunications by installing two Standard A earth stations. Current projects include financing Vietnam's new BDH fiber optic backbone, and financing construction of a VSAT network.

<td valign=top align=left>Sapura won an 8-year BCC to operate payphones with the Ho Chi Minh City P&T. Sapura installed over 836 of its cardphones in Ho Chi Minh City, 35 in Vung Tau, and 22 in Song Be, as of April 1996. By year-end 1996, they plan to install over 1,200 cardphones. In the first three years of its BCC, Sapura has agreed to install 1,500 cardphones in the Ho Chi Minh City area. Sapura also operates payphones in Hanoi under a trial agreement.
</table>
</center>
<br>

Much of the credit for MobiFone's quick success, says Comvik's marketing manager Martin Sjolund, goes to the Vietnamese side. VMS sales and marketing director Nguyen Manh Thang seems to be on his Ericsson continually. "Our company is a service, not a hand-set," he says. According to Thang, the ubiquitous billboards and other ads help advertise "our strongest points, better service, such as roaming in 22 provinces already, and cheaper price. We advertise everything; in May it was image. But best is word of mouth. And with competition (Vinaphone), we must provide the best service." MobiFone aims to keep 60% (of a projected 300,000 subscribers) marketshare in five years, while facing up to three competitors. Vinaphone, he added, should have up to 25% share, but "may not be a competitor in the future."<p>

<img src="../october96/cover/pic2.gif" valign=top align=right alt="Telecom Shop Photo">

<img src="../caps/ecap.gif" align=left border=0 alt="E">xperience in this market causes many surveyed to emphasize the caveats, as well, in part based on METC's false start last year. Says one would-be carrier, "A lot of games can be played without a backbone of legislation. The more carriers the better, but someone needs to fight the regulation battle first. Local, cellular, long distance-fields of business should be defined."<p>

Even without such delineation, and with complaints, players recognize they are operating in a market characterized by quick growth, a credit-worthy partner in VNPT, and the government's attention. In cooperating with foreign partners and gaining training and technology VNPT's goals are becoming grander. A year ago, the monopoly announced its interest in launching a $250 million TV and communication satellite by the year 2000 with outside financing (but industry privately balked). Recently the subject has resurrected. Market leader Alcatel, according to official press, has made a bid to launch "VINALSAT."<p>

However, foreigners and Vietnamese officials note that despite achievements, training remains a key element, especially in terms of technology transfer. A visitor recently arrived promptly at DGPT (the state telecom regulator) headquarters for a meeting with an official known for his clear explanations, but still missed his appointment. Why? The guard receiving visitors repeatedly misdialed his new phone, over the course of half an hour.<p>

<center>
<font size=+1>See Related Articles<br><a href="../october96/related2.html">Vietnam Online</a>   <font size=+1>|</font>   <a href="../october96/related1.html">VNPT's Ingenious "108 Girls"</a>
</font></center><br>

